00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:14.102
but there are a lot
of problems in it.

00:22:14.102 --> 00:22:16.200
And I want to talk to
you about a few of those,

00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:17.660
but I also want
to talk about how

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:19.840
to create magical experiences.

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:23.750
Now I don't blame people
for feeling somewhat

00:22:23.750 --> 00:22:25.930
negative toward the art
of magic in general.

00:22:25.930 --> 00:22:28.760
Because often, it seems like
a lot of magical presentations

00:22:28.760 --> 00:22:30.747
that people see do
one of two things.

00:22:30.747 --> 00:22:32.705
Either they're not
challenging intellectually--

00:22:32.705 --> 00:22:34.980
they insult you and
your intelligence

00:22:34.980 --> 00:22:38.300
by pretending that you
don't know that there's

00:22:38.300 --> 00:22:43.910
a string floating the
dollar, or the magician

00:22:43.910 --> 00:22:46.039
gives you the impression
that he expects

00:22:46.039 --> 00:22:47.580
you to believe that
he actually holds

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:50.300
the powers that his
illusions are replicating.

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:52.790
This kind of insults
your intellect,

00:22:52.790 --> 00:22:55.670
like you know that
he's not a wizard.

00:22:55.670 --> 00:22:56.870
This is clear.

00:22:56.870 --> 00:22:59.330
He's an illusionist.

00:22:59.330 --> 00:23:00.950
Either that, or
magic is presented

00:23:00.950 --> 00:23:03.577
as a puzzle that pits the
audience against the magician

00:23:03.577 --> 00:23:05.160
in some sort of
twisted battle of wits

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:09.790
where if the magician
fools you, you lose.

00:23:09.790 --> 00:23:12.590
If he doesn't, then the
magic is ruined, right?

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:15.410
None of these are ideal.

00:23:15.410 --> 00:23:17.190
Now that being said,
I do believe strongly

00:23:17.190 --> 00:23:19.870
that magic has the
potential to be

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:24.064
a very intellectual
and serious art form.

00:23:24.064 --> 00:23:25.730
And that's because
what magic ultimately

00:23:25.730 --> 00:23:28.900
deals with is something
very, very powerful, and that

00:23:28.900 --> 00:23:32.780
is the nature of
truth-- what is reality.

00:23:32.780 --> 00:23:34.560
What is our reality?

00:23:34.560 --> 00:23:37.080
At any moment, at
any given time,

00:23:37.080 --> 00:23:40.530
the most important
basic belief you form

00:23:40.530 --> 00:23:44.147
is what is real--
what is my reality.

00:23:44.147 --> 00:23:46.480
And it's from this belief
that we form all of our others

00:23:46.480 --> 00:23:48.521
and if we make errors in
this judgment, obviously

00:23:48.521 --> 00:23:50.910
can have very dire consequences.

00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:54.767
When I'm walking into
Google across the street,

00:23:54.767 --> 00:23:56.600
if I make an error in
my judgment of reality

00:23:56.600 --> 00:24:00.970
and I don't see the car
coming, obviously bad things.

00:24:00.970 --> 00:24:04.020
If I err consistently in less
physically perilous ways,

00:24:04.020 --> 00:24:08.192
mental ways, psychological
ways, I'm a schizophrenic.

00:24:08.192 --> 00:24:10.270
This "what is real"
is one of our most

00:24:10.270 --> 00:24:13.050
central and
foundational beliefs.

00:24:13.050 --> 00:24:14.630
And it's always
humming along right

00:24:14.630 --> 00:24:16.840
under our level of
conscious awareness.

00:24:16.840 --> 00:24:21.630
And I think it can be with
magic, a very profound thing.

00:24:21.630 --> 00:24:23.465
Profound, but not the point.

00:24:23.465 --> 00:24:25.090
The key to creating
magical experiences

00:24:25.090 --> 00:24:28.350
is not to convince your audience
that they may or may not

00:24:28.350 --> 00:24:29.430
be sane.

00:24:29.430 --> 00:24:32.980
The key to creating magical
experiences, I think, is this.

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:37.620
So number one, we must
understand the assumptions

00:24:37.620 --> 00:24:39.680
and expectations
of our audience.

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:41.020
Pencils, please?

00:24:41.020 --> 00:24:46.220
Number two, we must break these
expectations and assumptions.

00:24:46.220 --> 00:24:47.720
And number three,
we must break them

00:24:47.720 --> 00:24:50.330
in a way that brings people
joy and also makes them

00:24:50.330 --> 00:24:52.680
question just what
is possible to have

00:24:52.680 --> 00:24:54.690
happen in an experience.

00:24:54.690 --> 00:24:58.780
Now as much as we all
like to think of ourselves

00:24:58.780 --> 00:25:02.090
as logical and rational
beings, we only

00:25:02.090 --> 00:25:06.480
have to look so far as our
news headlines, even ourselves,

00:25:06.480 --> 00:25:10.400
when in anger or in love or
drunk or whatever, to realize

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:13.570
how wrong of an
assumption this is.

00:25:13.570 --> 00:25:17.940
No matter how much we like
to praise our rational side,

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:21.610
there's no arguing that we
are ruled by our emotions.

00:25:21.610 --> 00:25:23.190
We are ruled by our emotions.

00:25:23.190 --> 00:25:26.030
And it's important to--
well, and sometimes this

00:25:26.030 --> 00:25:28.580
can be a very bad thing,
because sometimes we

00:25:28.580 --> 00:25:31.900
find ourselves acting in ways
that we don't want to act,

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:35.740
or not being able to do the
things that we want to do.

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:39.480
For example, we all know
that it's important to floss

00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:41.110
twice a day, that we
should eat healthy

00:25:41.110 --> 00:25:44.590
and that we should exercise
and we should save money.

00:25:44.590 --> 00:25:47.810
And yet, how many of us
actually do these things?

00:25:47.810 --> 00:25:48.522
I don't.

00:25:48.522 --> 00:25:49.480
I don't know about you.

00:25:49.480 --> 00:25:52.600
Maybe you guys are better
individuals than I.

00:25:52.600 --> 00:25:56.730
As we all are, as people who
create experiences for others,

00:25:56.730 --> 00:26:00.430
it's vital to know
and understand

00:26:00.430 --> 00:26:03.550
this gap between the logic
and the emotional side

00:26:03.550 --> 00:26:05.720
and what is the
most strong pull?

00:26:05.720 --> 00:26:07.800
Obviously, emotion.

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:12.730
Now also of course,
what's the best way

00:26:12.730 --> 00:26:16.110
to engage with someone's
emotional side?

00:26:16.110 --> 00:26:18.610
Now I, if you remember,
break expectations.

00:26:18.610 --> 00:26:19.360
Number two, right?

00:26:19.360 --> 00:26:22.620
I think surprising people by
breaking their expectations is

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:26.430
the most powerful way to engage
with their emotional side.

00:26:26.430 --> 00:26:31.100
And this makes sense,
surprising is it breaks you out

00:26:31.100 --> 00:26:33.580
of your day-to-day assumptions.

00:26:33.580 --> 00:26:38.220
Now of course,
surprise is powerful.

00:26:38.220 --> 00:26:42.370
But surprise in general is
not necessarily a good thing.

00:26:42.370 --> 00:26:45.080
If I ask, who likes
to be surprised,

00:26:45.080 --> 00:26:48.130
it's like, very few
people like surprises.

00:26:48.130 --> 00:26:51.090
But that's because most the
time when you guys engage

00:26:51.090 --> 00:26:52.930
with surprises it's
a negative thing.

00:26:52.930 --> 00:26:55.950
If my friend expects me to
pick him up from the airport

00:26:55.950 --> 00:26:59.290
and I surprise him by not
picking him up at the airport,

00:26:59.290 --> 00:27:02.550
