00:33:05.125 --> 00:33:10.020
But I suppose what fascinates
me about magic in large part

00:33:10.020 --> 00:33:13.060
is the experience of what
is possible versus what

00:33:13.060 --> 00:33:13.670
is impossible.

00:33:13.670 --> 00:33:15.380
I think it's a
really powerful thing

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:17.580
to be able to break
people's expectations

00:33:17.580 --> 00:33:20.370
and to show them something and
have them jarred really quickly

00:33:20.370 --> 00:33:24.667
out of their just kind
of neutral baseline

00:33:24.667 --> 00:33:25.500
level of experience.

00:33:28.015 --> 00:33:29.890
Another thing that
fascinates me about magic,

00:33:29.890 --> 00:33:31.420
one of my favorite
parts about it,

00:33:31.420 --> 00:33:36.390
is how it makes people fools.

00:33:36.390 --> 00:33:39.370
I love more than anything else
being deceived by something

00:33:39.370 --> 00:33:41.550
because it shows
me my ignorance.

00:33:41.550 --> 00:33:44.460
I think magic is
one of the best ways

00:33:44.460 --> 00:33:48.890
to learn what it is about your
perceptions and your level

00:33:48.890 --> 00:33:51.530
of attention that
are completely false.

00:33:51.530 --> 00:33:53.080
People can be fooled-- everyone.

00:33:53.080 --> 00:33:56.040
And that has implications
on so many spectrums,

00:33:56.040 --> 00:34:00.469
from the skepticism spectrum
of God doesn't exist

00:34:00.469 --> 00:34:02.010
and religion and
alternative medicine

00:34:02.010 --> 00:34:04.870
and stuff all the way to
just day-to-day things,

00:34:04.870 --> 00:34:06.689
not being aware of the
intentions of people

00:34:06.689 --> 00:34:08.730
you're hanging out with,
like that kind of stuff.

00:34:08.730 --> 00:34:12.380
So I think it does
have a lot of meaning

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:13.866
behind it and importance.

00:34:13.866 --> 00:34:15.949
AUDIENCE: I think one of
the points you brought up

00:34:15.949 --> 00:34:21.810
was about the expectations
or the cool sign stuff.

00:34:21.810 --> 00:34:25.230
One of the kids' class I was
there and said, hey magic,

00:34:25.230 --> 00:34:25.889
look.

00:34:25.889 --> 00:34:28.810
There's a device here which
I can press a few buttons,

00:34:28.810 --> 00:34:31.340
talk to and see somebody
around the world.

00:34:31.340 --> 00:34:34.130
And people are like, "So what?"

00:34:34.130 --> 00:34:36.400
The kids, basically,
they have-- they

00:34:36.400 --> 00:34:38.000
don't think that I do magic.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:40.250
So that's a very
good point, like this

00:34:40.250 --> 00:34:43.317
could have been actually the
grand magic 100 years ago

00:34:43.317 --> 00:34:44.400
if you had shown somebody.

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:45.730
KEVIN BLAKE: Oh yeah.

00:34:45.730 --> 00:34:47.920
I mean, all the technology
that we live in right

00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:52.469
now is completely
impossible, or just comes

00:34:52.469 --> 00:34:54.179
so out of the realm
of imagination

00:34:54.179 --> 00:34:56.260
of a human of 100 years ago.

00:34:56.260 --> 00:34:58.900
It is just mind
boggling what we can do.

00:34:58.900 --> 00:35:01.660
AUDIENCE: So what I find
fascinating is the small tricks

00:35:01.660 --> 00:35:05.490
you do still fascinates people
versus they are completely

00:35:05.490 --> 00:35:09.210
oblivious to the fact which
is, you are living under magic

00:35:09.210 --> 00:35:12.330
which was not possible 100 years
ago or something like this--

00:35:12.330 --> 00:35:14.460
fly around the world
and go somewhere and--

00:35:14.460 --> 00:35:17.750
KEVIN BLAKE: I think one of
the challenges of magic right

00:35:17.750 --> 00:35:23.340
now is trying to continue to
evolve alongside technology.

00:35:23.340 --> 00:35:25.480
Because a lot of
things-- and that's

00:35:25.480 --> 00:35:27.710
one of the problems with
the magician assuming-- what

00:35:27.710 --> 00:35:30.250
I said earlier-- like a
magician assuming that you know

00:35:30.250 --> 00:35:34.860
or expecting you to believe
that he has magical powers.

00:35:34.860 --> 00:35:38.430
Like, it's insulting to watch a
magician perform and then feel

00:35:38.430 --> 00:35:41.530
as though he wants you to
believe that he can levitate

00:35:41.530 --> 00:35:43.770
something or to stick
a spike through a woman

00:35:43.770 --> 00:35:48.312
or to have-- at this
age of technology

00:35:48.312 --> 00:35:50.270
and advanced technology
and that kind of stuff,

00:35:50.270 --> 00:35:52.430
we have a very large
understanding of what

00:35:52.430 --> 00:35:54.580
is impossible and
what's possible.

00:35:54.580 --> 00:35:58.430
Now we all know you cannot
levitate something with

00:35:58.430 --> 00:36:00.160
your mind.

00:36:00.160 --> 00:36:01.270
You can't do that.

00:36:01.270 --> 00:36:03.910
And so I think one
of the challenges is,

00:36:03.910 --> 00:36:05.520
and one of the
challenges that magic

00:36:05.520 --> 00:36:08.080
a struggling with in large
part, in a lot of areas,

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:11.050
is these magicians who
continue to perform

00:36:11.050 --> 00:36:14.180
these rudimentary and
old-style-- impressive

00:36:14.180 --> 00:36:16.680
when we didn't have such
an understanding of what

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:19.030
the world is like, but
not impressive anymore.

00:36:19.030 --> 00:36:21.020
Floating a little
ball on a handkerchief

00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:24.040
like you know that
that can't work.

00:36:24.040 --> 00:36:26.870
So it doesn't impress anymore.

00:36:26.870 --> 00:36:28.750
AUDIENCE: Yeah, what
are the magicians

00:36:28.750 --> 00:36:32.250
