00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:51.777
I saw him a few weeks
ago at the Magic Castle

00:36:51.777 --> 00:36:53.860
when he was performing
there with a friend of his.

00:36:53.860 --> 00:36:57.270
And he has a wonderful,
wonderful performance.

00:36:57.270 --> 00:36:59.120
So I recommend you
all go see his.

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:02.110
In terms of famous
magicians, there's one--

00:37:02.110 --> 00:37:04.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:04.860 --> 00:37:08.040
In terms of famous
magicians, of course

00:37:08.040 --> 00:37:12.300
we have very few that you
guys probably would know.

00:37:12.300 --> 00:37:14.200
A man who is a huge
inspiration to me

00:37:14.200 --> 00:37:15.954
is a man named Darren Brown.

00:37:15.954 --> 00:37:18.370
Does anyone here know who
Darren Brown is, except for him?

00:37:18.370 --> 00:37:18.660
Yeah?

00:37:18.660 --> 00:37:19.400
We got a few?

00:37:19.400 --> 00:37:20.750
Two?

00:37:20.750 --> 00:37:23.700
So you'll know he's
amazing, is he not?

00:37:23.700 --> 00:37:27.080
He is a Englishman,
a British guy

00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:31.140
who does similar psychological
hypnotism, all sorts

00:37:31.140 --> 00:37:34.950
of incredible presentations
that involve magic but are not

00:37:34.950 --> 00:37:35.580
just magic.

00:37:35.580 --> 00:37:36.497
They go way beyond it.

00:37:36.497 --> 00:37:38.163
So I highly recommend
you check him out.

00:37:38.163 --> 00:37:38.830
He is awesome.

00:37:38.830 --> 00:37:43.150
And he definitely inspired me
and almost every other magician

00:37:43.150 --> 00:37:45.816
that you'll run into these days.

00:37:45.816 --> 00:37:46.840
AUDIENCE: So sorry.

00:37:46.840 --> 00:37:48.810
I missed the first part.

00:37:48.810 --> 00:37:53.484
How early in your life
you started doing this?

00:37:53.484 --> 00:37:55.900
KEVIN BLAKE: I got into magic,
as I said, when I was nine.

00:37:55.900 --> 00:37:58.070
But I didn't actually
start doing magic

00:37:58.070 --> 00:38:00.310
until I was maybe, like, 12.

00:38:00.310 --> 00:38:03.250
And then that my first
actual public performance

00:38:03.250 --> 00:38:04.610
was in high school.

00:38:04.610 --> 00:38:07.100
My first full theater
show was in college.

00:38:07.100 --> 00:38:12.150
And so I am very new at
this in terms of stage time.

00:38:12.150 --> 00:38:17.370
I've only put on about, maybe,
30 shows, 30 full shows.

00:38:17.370 --> 00:38:21.192
And I hope to continue to
improve and to perform more.

00:38:21.192 --> 00:38:23.150
AUDIENCE: Talking about
manipulating audiences,

00:38:23.150 --> 00:38:25.280
what is the most surprising
thing an audience has

00:38:25.280 --> 00:38:28.125
done to you?

00:38:28.125 --> 00:38:30.810
KEVIN BLAKE:
Interesting question.

00:38:30.810 --> 00:38:36.970
Surprising thing an audience
has done to me-- well,

00:38:36.970 --> 00:38:40.110
I think probably
about two years ago, I

00:38:40.110 --> 00:38:42.330
was performing a routine
that maybe some of you guys

00:38:42.330 --> 00:38:44.913
have seen on, like, "America's
Got Talent" or something, where

00:38:44.913 --> 00:38:48.020
someone has a bunch
of-- a big spike

00:38:48.020 --> 00:38:52.270
under either in paper bags
or like under styrofoam cups.

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:54.060
And I was performing
this routine

00:38:54.060 --> 00:38:57.540
and you smash the ones that
it's not in, obviously,

00:38:57.540 --> 00:39:01.790
and with the one that
it's in unsmashed.

00:39:01.790 --> 00:39:05.060
So I was doing this
with a woman on stage

00:39:05.060 --> 00:39:06.110
who was helping me out.

00:39:06.110 --> 00:39:09.160
And there's a safety
mechanism built

00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:11.750
into the trick where hopefully
if it's about to go wrong,

00:39:11.750 --> 00:39:13.310
she will stop me.

00:39:13.310 --> 00:39:17.240
And the audience also will
hopefully scream and stuff.

00:39:17.240 --> 00:39:19.240
This didn't happen.

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:21.530
There was no safety mechanism,
and I stabbed myself

00:39:21.530 --> 00:39:22.529
in the hand with a nail.

00:39:22.529 --> 00:39:25.257
So that was-- but
continued the show.

00:39:25.257 --> 00:39:26.090
The show must go on.

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:31.140
And what was worse is
that I had asked someone

00:39:31.140 --> 00:39:33.400
in the audience who was
medically trained to help me

00:39:33.400 --> 00:39:33.900
out.

00:39:33.900 --> 00:39:35.110
I had it first aid kit.

00:39:35.110 --> 00:39:37.509
I still got it right in
here, a first aid kit.

00:39:37.509 --> 00:39:39.300
I said, do you know
how to bandage someone?

00:39:39.300 --> 00:39:39.800
Good.

00:39:39.800 --> 00:39:42.390
It's supposed to all be for
show, build the tension.

00:39:42.390 --> 00:39:43.200
No.

00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:46.110
She didn't know
how to bandage me.

00:39:46.110 --> 00:39:50.480
She lied about being
first aid trained,

00:39:50.480 --> 00:39:52.860
and I was just like, help
me out with the bandage.

00:39:52.860 --> 00:39:54.821
And she says, I don't
know how to do it.

00:39:54.821 --> 00:39:56.320
And I was like, OK
I'll do it myself

00:39:56.320 --> 00:39:58.278
and then continued the
show and kicked her out.

00:39:58.278 --> 00:40:03.120
So that was the show.

00:40:03.120 --> 00:40:03.880
Yeah, questions?

00:40:03.880 --> 00:40:05.110
MALE SPEAKER: You
told that story

00:40:05.110 --> 00:40:06.860
when I saw you and I
thought it was a joke

00:40:06.860 --> 00:40:07.920
and I thought it was
part of the show.

00:40:07.920 --> 00:40:09.050
KEVIN BLAKE: It's very serious.

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:09.610
Very serious.

00:40:09.610 --> 00:40:12.900
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering
the one we did with the coin,

00:40:12.900 --> 00:40:14.810
if you've ever had
anyone while they

00:40:14.810 --> 00:40:16.310
have their hands
behind their back--

00:40:16.310 --> 00:40:16.630
KEVIN BLAKE: Win a dollar?

00:40:16.630 --> 00:40:17.588
Put it in their pocket.

00:40:17.588 --> 00:40:19.336
AUDIENCE: Put it
in their pocket?

00:40:19.336 --> 00:40:20.086
KEVIN BLAKE: Yeah.

00:40:20.086 --> 00:40:22.400
Read your mind.

00:40:22.400 --> 00:40:24.140
Yes, this has happened.

00:40:24.140 --> 00:40:28.290
And hopefully, by
the way that they act

00:40:28.290 --> 00:40:30.640
and the little smirk on
their face, you can guess.

00:40:30.640 --> 00:40:32.240
Often when I'm doing
this, I'll say,

00:40:32.240 --> 00:40:33.700
you didn't put it in
your pocket did you?

00:40:33.700 --> 00:40:34.800
And they'll say, oh, I did.

00:40:34.800 --> 00:40:35.716
And it's a win, right?

00:40:35.716 --> 00:40:37.480
But I didn't do that
this time because I

00:40:37.480 --> 00:40:40.657
was so confident with you, Ryan.

00:40:40.657 --> 00:40:42.240
So yes, this is
something does happen.

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:45.665
But there are ways
to get around that.

00:40:45.665 --> 00:40:49.680
AUDIENCE: So do you watch for
facial expressions and Paul

00:40:49.680 --> 00:40:52.430
Ekman and "Lie To Me"
and all that stuff?

00:40:52.430 --> 00:40:55.450
KEVIN BLAKE: I don't watch
the show "Lie To Me."

00:40:55.450 --> 00:40:57.820
But a part of the
stuff that I've

00:40:57.820 --> 00:40:59.530
tried to learn as a
magician, because I

00:40:59.530 --> 00:41:02.962
think it very much makes
your performance better,

00:41:02.962 --> 00:41:04.420
is to be able to
read your audience

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:06.744
and read your participant.

00:41:06.744 --> 00:41:08.160
So the people who
come on a stage,

00:41:08.160 --> 00:41:11.080
it's vitally important to watch
what they're doing, how they're

00:41:11.080 --> 00:41:14.180
acting, and then use
that to your advantage,

00:41:14.180 --> 00:41:16.990
whether calling out
different things, like I'm

00:41:16.990 --> 00:41:20.782
sure all of you guys saw when
I said, left or I said right.

00:41:20.782 --> 00:41:21.740
I don't remember which.

00:41:21.740 --> 00:41:25.300
But you gave a huge
little half smirk.

00:41:25.300 --> 00:41:26.830
Huge little-- sorry about that.

00:41:26.830 --> 00:41:31.540
You gave a very obvious
little twitch of your mouth.

00:41:31.540 --> 00:41:32.870
Did we see this?

00:41:32.870 --> 00:41:33.400
I saw it.

00:41:33.400 --> 00:41:35.316
I don't know how obvious
this is to audiences.

00:41:35.316 --> 00:41:38.560
But this kind of thing
is very, very good

00:41:38.560 --> 00:41:41.370
to call out during
a show or to seem

00:41:41.370 --> 00:41:43.634
as though you're
using that to predict.

00:41:43.634 --> 00:41:45.050
So yeah, it's part
of the training

00:41:45.050 --> 00:41:46.508
but it's definitely
not everything.

